[5]
Date: 13 Oct 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: New York Times, 13 Oct 2001 [edited]
<http://www.nytimes.com/2001/10/13/nyregion/13HAND.html>

F.B.I. Did Not Test Letter to NBC [n]or Immediately Notify City Hall
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Although the Federal Bureau of Investigation was notified on 25 Sep 2001
about a suspicious letter sent to NBC, neither the letter, nor the
powder residue inside it were tested until at least 2 weeks later,
when a private doctor notified city public health officials about a
troubling skin condition in the news assistant who had opened the
letter, officials acknowledged yesterday. F.B.I. officials said that
after the agency was notified of the envelope containing white powder on
25 Sep 2001, it did not pick up the letter until the next day and then did
not analyze the powder itself nor did it attempt to take tissue samples
from the employee, identified as a 38-year-old assistant to Tom Brokaw,
agency officials said.
"That, unfortunately, did not take place," said Barry W. Mawn, special
agent in charge of the F.B.I.'s New York office. Further, New York City
officials were not informed of the preliminary inquiry until days later.
On Sept. 25., an assistant to Mr. Brokaw opened a letter postmarked from
St. Petersburg, Fla., filled with white powder, according to law
enforcement officials. Network officials, immediately suspicious, called
the F.B.I.
On 28 Sep 2001, the NBC employee, whom the network did not identify,
developed a strange sore on her chest. Nervous, she went to see Dr.
Richard Fried, a Manhattan infectious disease specialist, said Dr.
Annetta Kimball, the doctor covering for Dr. Fried, who could not be
reached last night. Armed with the description of the rash - which she
described as central scarring surrounded by a lot of swelling - the
doctor likely consulted his textbooks to nail down what was going on.
Dr. Kimball said that Dr. Fried suspected that his patient had been
exposed to anthrax, and immediately prescribed Cipro.
"There is a good chance he had never seen anthrax before," said Dr.
Kimball. "This is New York City, not an agricultural area." He also took
cultures from a wound she developed, but those swabs were negative for
anthrax, she said.
At some point, officials and Dr. Kimball said, the patient was believed
to have visited a dermatologist and possibly another infectious disease
expert. One of those doctors notified the city's Health Department on
6 Oct 2001 of a possible case of anthrax. The city has among the most
sophisticated epidemiologists and labs of any municipal or state health
laboratory in the country.
[Byline: Jennifer Steinhauer & Jim Dwyer]
